<DOC><DOCNO> AP890421-0120 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-89 1519EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Brazil-Floods     04-21 0164</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Brazil-Floods,0169</SECOND><HEAD>Floods Leave 46,000 Homeless in Northern Brazil</HEAD><DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Heavy rains and floods have left46,000 people homeless in Ceara state in northeastern Brazil, civildefense authorities said Friday.   The Jaguaribe River, one of Ceara's main rivers, overflowed itsbanks and left 7 feet of water in fields and towns in ninemunicipalities, according to civil defense worker Socorro Martins.   ``The crops are lost and there are serious outbreaks ofpneumonia, fever and diarrhea,'' Miss Martins said by telephonefrom Fortaleza, the Ceara state capital 1,700 miles northeast ofRio de Janeiro.   The homeless, mostly poor rural workers, were being put up inschools, government buildings and canvas tents, she said.   Gov. Tasso Jereissati declared a state of emergency in the nineaffected townships, Miss Martins said.   Although it is the rainy season in the usually arid northeast,showers have fallen almost without letup since February, MissMartins said. More rain was forecast in the coming days.</TEXT></DOC>